<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"><channel><title>NYT &gt; Technology</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/section/technology</link><description>Technology industry news, commentary, and analysis, with reporting on big tech, startups, and internet culture. The New York Times is a hub for conversation about news and ideas.</description><atom:link rel="self" href="https://rss.nytimes.com/services/xml/rss/nyt/Technology.xml" type="application/rss+xml" /><item><title>OpenAI Leans Toward Holding Up I.P.O. Until Next Year</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/25/technology/openai-ipo-artificial-intelligence.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/25/technology/openai-ipo-artificial-intelligence.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/25/technology/openai-ipo-artificial-intelligence.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The A.I. company’s advisers are pushing its chief executive, Sam Altman, to move slowly after SpaceX’s stock has been volatile and as the start-up grapples with financial challenges.</description><dc:creator>Rob Copeland and Mike Isaac</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Jun 2026 20:31:22 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">IPO</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Stocks</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Bonds</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Startup</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Venture capital</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Anthropic</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">OpenAI</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">SpaceX</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Sam Altman</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Sarah Friar</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/25/multimedia/25biz-openai-ipo-sam-flvk/25biz-openai-ipo-sam-flvk-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Haiyun Jiang/The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>Sam Altman, the chief executive of OpenAI, has pushed for a trillion-dollar I.P.O.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Trump Plans to Name Adam Candeub as Antitrust Chief in Justice Dept.</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/25/technology/trump-antitrust-doj-adam-candeub.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/25/technology/trump-antitrust-doj-adam-candeub.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/25/technology/trump-antitrust-doj-adam-candeub.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>President Trump plans to nominate a tech critic and telecommunications lawyer, Adam Candeub, to lead the division.</description><dc:creator>Cecilia Kang</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Jun 2026 23:03:26 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">US Politics</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mergers and Acquisitions</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Competition law</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Presidential Election of 2024</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Decisions and Verdicts</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Donald Trump</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Justice Department</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">FCC</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">FTC</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/25/multimedia/25biz-doj-antitrust-Adam-Candeub-cphg/25biz-doj-antitrust-Adam-Candeub-cphg-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Alex Kent/The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>If confirmed by the Senate, Adam Candeub, the general counsel at the Federal Communications Commission, would lead the antitrust division at Department of Justice, above. </media:description></media:content></item><item><title>China Takes Supercomputer Crown From U.S. For First Time Since 2017</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/technology/china-supercomputer-crown-us.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/technology/china-supercomputer-crown-us.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/technology/china-supercomputer-crown-us.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>A supercomputer in Shenzhen was declared the world’s fastest. It uses only standard microprocessors and not the special-purpose chips called graphics processing units.</description><dc:creator>Don Clark</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 23 Jun 2026 09:02:27 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">China</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Supercomputer</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computer Chip</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">International relations</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Cloud computing</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">ARM Holdings</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Shenzhen</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">internal-open-access-from-nl</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/24/business/23biz-china-supercomputer-wuxi/23biz-china-supercomputer-wuxi-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Xu Congjun/VCG, via Getty Images</media:credit><media:description>China’s National Supercomputing Center in Wuxi in 2020. LineShine, a supercomputer in Shenzhen, has been declared the world’s fastest.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>IBM Unveils New Method to Make Smaller Computer Chip Parts</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/25/technology/ibm-technology-tinier-chips.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/25/technology/ibm-technology-tinier-chips.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/25/technology/ibm-technology-tinier-chips.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Industry leaders had worried that innovations in chip miniaturization were no longer possible.</description><dc:creator>Don Clark</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Jun 2026 10:00:16 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computer Chip</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">IBM</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/25/multimedia/25biz-ibm-chips-zjvp/25biz-ibm-chips-zjvp-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Bryan Derballa for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>A silicon wafer full of microchips at the IBM research facility in Albany, N.Y. Industry analysts briefed on an IBM announcement were impressed, while noting that the approach would face competition.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Tesla Driver Using Autopilot Crashes Into Home in Texas and Kills a Woman, Officials Say</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/21/us/tesla-autopilot-crash-texas.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/21/us/tesla-autopilot-crash-texas.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/21/us/tesla-autopilot-crash-texas.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The driver told investigators he was using the vehicle’s automated-driver system when the vehicle left the roadway and crashed into a house in Harris County, Texas.</description><dc:creator>Johnny Diaz</dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 21 Jun 2026 19:49:15 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Driverless Cars</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Self-Driving Cars</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tesla</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Fatalities</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">casualties</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Car Crash</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Electric Cars and Hybrids</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Harris County</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Katy</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/21/multimedia/21xp-tesla-vtmq/21xp-tesla-vtmq-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Mike Blake/Reuters</media:credit><media:description>The dashboard of a Tesla model using a driver-assistance system in California.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Meta Has Created a Prediction Markets App</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/technology/meta-prediction-markets-app.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/technology/meta-prediction-markets-app.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/23/technology/meta-prediction-markets-app.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The experimental app, internally called “Arena,” would be independent of Facebook and Instagram. It could compete for attention with Polymarket and Kalshi, the biggest prediction markets.</description><dc:creator>Mike Isaac and David Yaffe-Bellany</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 23 Jun 2026 16:40:17 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Meta</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Prediction Markets</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mobile Apps</category><categ